<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="description" content="LGA Briefing" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>DDB0170</title></head><body><div><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Local Government Association – Written evidence</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Introduction</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.63pt; padding-left:4.37pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The Local Government Association (LGA) welcomes the opportunity to comment on the content of the draft Deregulation Bill. Responses to the questions posed by the draft Deregulation Bill Committee have been embedded within the content of the submission where appropriate.</span></li></ol><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.63pt; padding-left:4.37pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">We welcome the move by the Government to reduce the legislative burden on business, civil society, individuals and public sector bodies. This approach is completely in line with our recently launched initiative “Rewiring Public Services”</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.63pt; padding-left:4.37pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">A number of the proposals within the draft Bill will benefit businesses and growth. However, the LGA believes that the draft Bill represents an opportunity to allow </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">local government to help further drive economic growth, by offering councils greater flexibilities and freedoms from central government control and regulation. In light of this the LGA has used this submission to propose a number of measures that should be included within the Bill when it returns to Parliament after scrutiny at draft stage.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.63pt; padding-left:4.37pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The LGA’s </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">“Rewiring Public Services” is an ambitious programme which provides much-needed solutions to how we can deliver public services within an ever-tightening fiscal environment. As part of this work, the LGA is advocating a radical new approach which would allow local authorities, through greater local autonomy, to help generate the economic growth that our nation so desperately needs. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.63pt; padding-left:4.37pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">‘Rewiring Public Services’ sets out a number of propositions which are relevant to the draft deregulation bill: </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">5.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Localised and simplified regulation linked to a clearly defined vision for the community and place. Local regulators work with businesses across the country on a daily basis to cut red tape and help them comply with the law. This creates an environment where businesses have the confidence to invest, grow and create new jobs. Our</span><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> ambition is for local government to be able to work with businesses in a local area to understand risks and determine what level of regulation is appropriate. Local trading standards, environmental health and licensing services are well placed to free up businesses from unnecessary regulation and can design and operate a scheme which is right for business and right for local communities, without central direction and prescription.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">5.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">A ‘local treasury’ and place based budgets to provide the incentive for a local budget for growth and choice, rather than individual budgets to fund individual services. A ‘local treasury’ could have the ability to flex business rates, and other taxes including, for example, tourist or sales taxes to support local economies. This model would also offer democratic empowerment by establishing an agreement between councils and taxpayers on the level of local taxation and their choices on spending decisions.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">5.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">A changed relationship between universities and cities and counties to link education more strongly to local economies. Despite the ground-breaking work of many university vice-chancellors who are playing an important role in driving a LEP or helping to attract inward investment into their locality, there are few financial incentives for the higher education sector to support their local economy. A ‘local treasury’ could provide such incentives to universities, to link innovation and education to the local economy.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">5.4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The development of clearer employer involvement in schools’ work on education outcomes, and the local leadership of skills and jobs initiatives, orchestrated through local government and linked to the needs of the local economic sub-region. These reforms are essential to tackle the 20% youth unemployment rate and the shocking skills mismatch we face. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The following comments have been tested against the principles outlined in “Rewiring Public Services”</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">and are in order of the clauses as they appear in the draft of the Bill.</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Apprenticeships (Clause 3)</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.63pt; padding-left:4.37pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">We welcome the drive to reduce associated bureaucracy for businesses wanting to take on apprentices. The Richard Review made some sound recommendations looking to improve the quality, reduce simplification, and increase the leverage of employers in the apprenticeship system. Nevertheless we have some concerns, and would like to build to:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.63pt; padding-left:4.37pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Incorporate a spatial dimension to target sectors</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">7.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Target sectors are currently set by the National Apprenticeship Service (NAS) centrally without consideration to variations in local economic conditions. As a result, apprenticeship priority areas make little sense to businesses in a number of places. For example, none of the current priority NAS sectors have resonated with Wolverhampton’s local economy. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">7.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">National statistics have cast doubt on the mixed performance of the apprenticeship system over successive administrations. In 2011 almost 70 per cent of new apprenticeship opportunities were taken by over 25s, one fifth of all apprenticeships lasted less than 6 months, and 84 per cent of the growth was in just 10 narrow occupations (source: National Audit Office, Adult Apprenticeships, 2012).</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">7.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">It is a positive step that employers themselves will help to determine apprenticeship sectors nationally, but it will be important to ensure smaller employers, or those in more unique and growing sectors, do not lose out. Local authorities and Local Enterprise Partnerships know their businesses best and can play a critical role in supporting them to grow and benefit from opportunities to take on apprentices.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">7.4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Local models are succeeding. Apprenticeship Hubs, Apprenticeship Training Associations and other efforts prove the added value of local leverage over provision. Essex County Council’s apprenticeship drive focused on key local growth sectors like marine technology, aviation, ports and logistics. It exceeded its target by 10 per cent, working with employers to help over 1,250 individuals into </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">apprenticeships of which 80 per cent successfully completed, much higher that 64 per cent average for national apprenticeship schemes.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">7.5.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">There are various options to build in local leverage with minimum bureaucracy, for example giving Local Enterprise Partnerships a role in setting the priority investment sectors for their area with the National Apprenticeship Service. This could include a ring-fenced amount of funding, targeted at growth sectors in each area, and continuing to support the development of apprenticeship hubs across all LEP areas.</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.63pt; padding-left:4.37pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Enable local authorities to ensure vulnerable people also benefit from provision of apprenticeships </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">8.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">There are various options to build in local leverage with minimum bureaucracy, for example giving LEPs a role in setting the priority investment sectors for their area with the National Apprenticeship Service, as highlighted in paragraph 7.5.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">8.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">It is important that employers drive a high quality apprenticeship system, but it is also important that people and communities are able to benefit from public investment. Local authorities have a statutory responsibility to ensure more vulnerable group, such as young people leaving care, the homeless or disabled people, are supported towards employment</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">8.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Despite having this responsibility, councils are side-lined from key provisions able to help more vulnerable groups towards work. The apprenticeships and new traineeships programmes aim to build a stronger relationship between providers and employers, which is important, but this should not be to the detriment of local authorities and the third sector groups looking out for the most vulnerable. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">8.4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Local authorities are already trying to this and are having some success, but this is in spite of the system rather than because of it. Newcastle City Council has developed an Apprenticeship Plus scheme, which helps young people to gain an apprenticeship. It supports young people in interview preparation and application, and for those not successful, it offers additional support to fill skills and pre-employment gaps.</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Hertfordshire County Council has reduced youth disengagement by 20 per cent, including a number of ‘at risk’ groups, by embedding apprenticeships and skills support into a wider five stage offer including basic skills and family support.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">8.5.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">It is important that local authorities are able to influence the market of provision on the behalf of these vulnerable groups, ensuring providers are incentivised to help them and linking it to other support they may be receiving. Without it, harder to help groups will continue to miss out. There are a number of ways that this could be achieved, for example by devolving additional incentive funding to local partnerships that can target specific companies to help specific groups of people.</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Right to Buy (Clause 20)</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.63pt; padding-left:4.37pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The current inflexibility of the Right to </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Buy</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> system has a number of consequences which undermine the ability of local authorities to invest in new build housing to meet local needs. Local authorities must have a greater say over the Right to </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Buy</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> to reflect local priorities and their local housing market. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The draft Deregulation Bill presents an opportunity to enable councils to maximise the receipts from Right to </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Buy</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> to reinvest in replacement homes while encouraging sales under the scheme. Relaxing the eligibility criteria makes these reforms more important than ever. A blanket discount cap, as is currently in place, ignores the large differences in property values up and down the country, and in some areas will not provide a discount sufficient to generate sales and vice versa. Greater flexibility should be provided to enable councils to set the Right to </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Buy</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> discount locally, to reflect local housing markets.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Many </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">councils</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> have reported increased pressure on their stock of one and two bedroom properties. However, the current approach contains an inbuilt disincentive to reinvest in one and two bedroom flats. This is because the current system is structured so as to limit the ability for local authorities to reclaim their outstanding debt on new properties </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">–  until</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> a property is 15 years old the law limits the Right to Buy discount to ensure that the purchase price of the property does not fall below what has been spent on building, buying, repairing or maintaining it</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">. After a property is 15 years old, this ‘cost floor’ does not apply. Sales after this time period can leave the authority operating at a loss. Extending the cost floor (i.e. the period that exists before the debt on the property is paid off) on new builds and flats from 15 to 25 years would remove this disincentive by ensuring that sales even at the maximum discount level would not incur a loss for the authority. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Under the current system, the amount of receipts kept by the Treasury is based on the predicted amount of Right to </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Buy</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> sales in each authority. This means that only when the Treasury has received the predicted amount does money become available to be retained locally. The restrictive criteria which accompany Homes and Communities Agency agreements to retain receipts locally also restrict the ability of local authorities to invest in housing. For example, the agreements limit councils to funding only 30 per cent of new build costs from Right to </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Buy</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> receipts, as well as limiting the use of other housing revenue account receipts as funding. The draft Deregulation Bill should allow for full retention of receipts and greater flexibility over how they are used. This would incentivise councils to use their assets, such as land, for replacement housing and could allow councils to bring development sites forward that may not be attractive or viable to other providers.</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Household waste: de-criminalisation (Clause 29)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Working towards the common aim of reducing landfill and general waste pollution councils and residents have transform recycling and waste services levels in the last decade. Since 2000, the proportion of household waste recycled has increased from 11 per cent to 43 per cent putting the UK on course to meet its EU recycling targets by 2020. At the same time resident satisfaction levels for council waste collection services have risen and are now at 86 per cent nationally. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Councils encourage recycling through raising awareness and providing information to residents about waste services and how waste and recycling should be presented. However in a small minority of cases, there are households who consistently fail to </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">comply with arrangements and cause a nuisance to neighbours by continually leaving rubbish out in the street or failing to separate waste for recycling. It is important that councils are able to tackle these problems since the waste from such residents can contaminate much larger quantities, making it unsuitable for recycling and significantly increasing the costs of disposal. The cost of this contamination is shared by all tax payers, the majority of whom have taken care to separate waste for recycling.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">In such instances, councils use a number of interventions including notices on bins, letters to householders and visits to the property to discuss how bins are used. The limited powers that councils have to issue fixed penalty notices in the case of serious and persistent misuse are only ever used as a last resort and after other means have been exhausted. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The most recent data from </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Defra</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> demonstrates that councils are using these powers proportionately: in 2008/9 a total of 876 fixed penalties were issued and pursued for payment, of which only 100 latterly involved criminal prosecutions due to non-payment. On average this is just over two penalties issued per council area each year or one for every 26,000 households. The powers to issue penalties and the ultimate sanction of prosecution serve as a backstop in extreme cases and a deterrent to wider misuse of waste and recycling facilities.</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The draft Bill proposes to remove the criminal sanction in England and stipulates that a civil penalty can only be issued following a series of letters and notices and where the actions of the householder cause nuisance or are detrimental to any amenities of the locality.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The current system functions well and existing powers are used only in extreme circumstances. Their predominant value is as a deterrent. There is no evidence that these powers are being used disproportionately and the LGA does not therefore see an evidence-based reason to change the system.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Removing the ultimate sanction of criminal prosecution will make enforcement more difficult for councils and undermine the effectiveness of the deterrent, as well as a council’s ability to tackle persistent misuse. Furthermore, councils will be prevented in many cases from taking civil enforcement action (since they can only issue fines in cases of nuisance and harm to local amenity. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The changes will also mean councils no longer have any enforcement powers in circumstances where residents persistently fail to comply with arrangements for separation of waste for recycling. This will significantly undermine councils’ efforts to work with their communities to increase recycling rates and reduce use of landfill sites and pollution. It will also increase the cost of disposing of contaminated waste. This is contrary to government policy to reduce contamination of recycling.</span></li></ol><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Requirement for local authorities and governing bodies to set targets (Clause 33)</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">This clause will remove a statutory power to allow the Secretary of State to make regulations requiring councils to set annual targets for the educational performance of maintained schools. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The regulations that were made under this power have already been withdrawn, a move supported by the LGA. As a result, the LGA supports this clause which seeks to bring the primary legislation in to line. </span></li></ol><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Power to </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">disapply</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline"> legislation no longer of practical use (Clause 51)</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The Bill introduces a new “power to </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">disapply</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> legislation no longer of practical use.” The meaning of the phrase “no longer of practical use” is not clear, neither is the use of the word “practical”. The phrase should either be defined on the face of the legislation, or strong commitments to thorough and meaningful consultation with relevant stakeholders should be given, before the power can be used. </span></li></ol><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">The growth duty (Clauses 58-61)</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">There is an irony that a deregulation Bill should introduce a new duty where one is not needed. We believe that enabling economic growth should underpin regulation. As a result of their wider community focus, councils already have a long tradition of promoting economic growth and of working in partnership with business and other stakeholders, including through Local Enterprise Partnerships (LEPs). Councils are playing key roles in enabling growth in the economy, promoting consumer and business confidence and supporting the private sector. With their local partners, councils have been attracting finance for, and investing themselves, in infrastructure and housing, regulating rogue traders and supporting local companies to grow and create jobs – in short, councils are getting on with promoting growth.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The Government must demonstrate the added value a growth duty would offer businesses and consumers, alongside a substantiated explanation of the outcomes that will be achieved if a statutory duty was introduced. There is a danger that focusing on a statutory duty risks creating a system of bureaucracy and monitoring, without actually achieving any real or tangible benefits for business.</span></li></ol><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Further deregulatory measures this draft Bill could bring forward</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Reducing licensing burdens on businesses</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The draft Deregulation Bill should be used as an opportunity to overhaul the current licensing system to encourage growth and give local communities the real ability to shape their neighbourhood and protect their high streets.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="27" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">We are disappointed that Government have not used the draft Deregulation Bill to implement a cross-Whitehall initiative to remove outdated or unnecessary licensing regimes. For example, the licences for performing animals and hypnotists should be abolished and there is the opportunity to create single, simplified licences for subjects such as licensed animal establishments, road closures, street activity and holiday premises.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="28" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The Government should also take this opportunity to provide a simplified approach to a number of licensing regimes that have emerged over the past hundred years. Each licensing regime has its own unique legal framework of renewal periods, supporting </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">documentation, inspection, statutory forms and appeals which are confusing for businesses. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="29" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">In “Rewiring Public Services” we propose that all licensing regimes should be based on a common legal framework, one which recognises the ‘licence for life’ principle under the Licensing Act. This principle only requires businesses to submit an annual fee rather than the complete a full, bureaucratic renewal for a licence. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="30" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Importantly, a simplified approach to licensing would legally embed the role of local licensing committees into all licence regimes, providing a transparent way of making policies and decisions accountable to both residents and businesses. With the licensing committee providing the true link to local priorities and risks, they should be given full power to remove licensing that is stifling growth and no longer appropriate in a local area. They should also be able to respond to emerging local risks, such as growing concerns in respect to the proliferation of shops with the same use (for example, betting shops, estate agents, fast food shops, and pay day loan companies) on local high streets.</span></li></ol><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Common sense in litigation</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="31" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">We are concerned that there are potential loopholes created by literal reading of regulations. For example Aylesbury District Council brought a</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> legal case</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> against a local taxi company earlier this year, following concerns that the company did not hold the proper license for operation. </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The case used legislation adopted locally 24 years previously, but failed because the Council were unable to provide documentary evidence that they had presented the original proposal to introduce the licensing regime to each parish council in their area</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="32" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The LGA is concerned that this case sets a dangerous precedent, which could be used to question long established decisions that have been conducted in an appropriate manner, applied consistently and are well understood by communities. The potential to question the basis for such decisions could prove costly to every single council and undermine the licensing policies at the heart of local communities.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="33" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The LGA proposes that the draft Deregulation Bill introduce a definitive statement that criminal or civil proceedings cannot be used to question whether a public authority has correctly implemented adoptive provisions if they were made more than 10 years previously, they have been continuously applied since they were adopted and the chief executive (or equivalent) certifies in writing that these conditions have been met.  </span></li></ol><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Removing the duty on local authorities to publish statutory notices in their local newspapers</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="34" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">It is a legal requirement for local authorities to pay to advertise public or statutory notices in local newspapers, covering a range of subjects such as informing residents about planned road closures, certain types of planning applications, road traffic orders</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">and changes to local education provision. </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The requirement dates back to 1972, a time when local and weekly newspapers and radio were popular sources of information. The last 41 years has seen vast changes in technology and shifts in consumer </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">preferences. This requirement remains in force despite evidence that the way people access news and information has changed significantly and the circulation of local newspapers is failing. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="35" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">We believe that the legal duty to publish statutory notices in local newspapers should be removed. T</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">his reform would </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">not</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> remove the duty on councils to inform their residents about statutory notices or any other area of council policy, it would simply allow them to decide whether or not the local newspaper was the best place to do this.</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> Such a change would be welcomed by local government as research shows that statutory notices are an expensive and ineffective way of communicating with residents. This is because:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 69.9pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-52.9pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">35.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Councils spend £26 million a year on public notices.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 70.9pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-52.9pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">35.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Eighty-four per cent of councils say there are more cost-effective ways to publish public notices, such as on websites and direct emails.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 70.9pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 70.9pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-52.9pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">35.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">42 per cent of councils are charged more by local newspapers to publish public notices than for other general advertising and the costs are continuing to rise.</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="36" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">These are substantial costs at a time when local government is facing the dual challenge of financial stability and sustainability.</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> Statutory notices are also out of date when evaluated in the context of recent technological advances in online communications (websites, </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Facebook</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">, twitter and e-mail being some of the most popular digital platforms).</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="37" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Research commissioned</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> by the Local Government Information Unit (LGIU) found that 9 out of 10 councils want the current legal requirements on public notices updated as they ‘are an out-of-date anachronism of the pre-electronic age.’</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Over three quarters of respondents would prefer to publish online as they argued that this was a better way to communicate, at less cost. The report recommended that the Government should investigate the possibility of supporting the development of a central online portal for the publication of public notices, along the lines of the model used in Scotland. This would seek to cut costs, free councils to decide how best to communicate with residents and create a central hub where residents can access the information they are interested in. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="38" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">By lifting the duty to publish statutory notices, the Government would be helping councils save money at a time of financial constraint, applying their own one in one out rule on new red tape (the publicity code being the new duty if it is passed) and adapting to the modern world in which the Bill compliments the Government’s ‘digital by default’ mantra.</span></li></ol><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Devolution</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="39" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The LGA is using “Rewiring Public Services” to drive the debate on the issue of devolution of decision making to councils, set against discussions on the role of the devolved nations. In light of this we would urge the committee to look at what can be passed on to English local governments when considering passing existing UK held powers to Wales, Scotland and Northern Ireland. </span></li></ol><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">About the Local Government Association</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">40</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The Local Government Association (LGA) is the national voice of local government.  We work with councils to support, promote and improve local government.</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">41</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">We are a politically-led, cross party organisation which works on behalf of councils to ensure local government has a strong, credible voice with national government.  We aim to influence and set the political agenda on the issues that matter to councils so they are able to deliver local solutions to national problems. The LGA covers every part of England and Wales, supporting local government as the most efficient and </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">accountable</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> part of the public sector.</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">16 September 2013</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:'Frutiger 45 Light'; font-size:10pt"> See </span><a href="http://www.local.gov.uk/campaigns"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:'Frutiger 45 Light'; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.local.gov.uk/campaigns</span></a><span style="font-family:'Frutiger 45 Light'; font-size:10pt"> for full details</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt"> Cost floor: Section 131 of the Housing Act 1985 limits the Right to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">Buy</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt"> discount to ensure that the purchase price of the property does not fall below what has been spent on building, buying, repairing or maintaining it over a certain period of time (relevant expenditure).</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt"> A summary of the case can be found on the council’s website at </span><a href="http://tinyurl.com/kd2yh5e"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt; text-decoration:underline">http://tinyurl.com/kd2yh5e</span></a><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn4"></a><a href="#_ftnref4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt"> The Local Government Information Unit, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt; font-style:italic">The case for radical reform: Part One, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">accessible at: </span><a href="http://www.lgiu.org.uk/publications/public-notices-the-case-for-radical-reform-part-1/"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.lgiu.org.uk/publications/public-notices-the-case-for-radical-reform-part-1/</span></a></p></body></html>